The paper discusses the use of distributed computing infrastructure (DCI) for high-performance computing, which falls under the category of Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC). The focus of the paper is on molecular dynamics simulations, which involves numerical analysis and algorithms (cs.NA). The simulations are applied to nanostructures under plastic deformation, which falls under the category of Computational Engineering, Finance, and Science (cs.CE). The paper also discusses statistical analysis of the simulation results, which falls under the category of Machine Learning and Statistics (cs.MS). Finally, the paper discusses the limitations and advantages of the DCI, which falls under the category of Software Engineering (cs.SE).
